WEBVTT

00:00:00.040 --> 00:00:01.620
Apologies, technical glitch.

00:00:01.630 --> 00:00:08.460
Today I'm going to talk a little bit about the,

00:00:08.460 --> 00:00:11.280
maybe we could call it the elephant in the room, I

00:00:11.280 --> 00:00:11.640
don't know.

00:00:11.680 --> 00:00:14.800
We're going to talk about authoritarianism and we're going

00:00:14.820 --> 00:00:20.470
to talk about the fact that openness as a concept and the

00:00:20.490 --> 00:00:26.180
way that the challenges and that the AT protocol was built to

00:00:26.180 --> 00:00:32.110
kind of contest weren't necessarily designed to imagine that the country

00:00:32.110 --> 00:00:35.830
in which it was built was going to be potentially an adversary

00:00:35.900 --> 00:00:36.160
.

00:00:36.200 --> 00:00:42.770
For context, I spent most of my career working in countries

00:00:42.770 --> 00:00:49.150
where people did not assume that their governments were supportive of their

00:00:49.170 --> 00:00:55.650
rights and freedoms and do not assume that a state is a

00:00:55.650 --> 00:00:58.590
benevolent actor in the service of their interests.

00:00:58.640 --> 00:01:01.970
And we have a, I think everybody knows very well,

00:01:01.970 --> 00:01:05.870
the Silicon Valley vision and version of the history of the Internet

00:01:05.880 --> 00:01:05.990
.

00:01:06.040 --> 00:01:10.990
It's worth noting that many people never experienced that version of

00:01:10.990 --> 00:01:16.360
the Internet and that the idea of the Internet as a space

00:01:16.360 --> 00:01:21.840
for political contestation basically emerged coterminous with the

00:01:21.840 --> 00:01:23.040
idea of the Internet.

00:01:23.080 --> 00:01:27.790
So, TomlNet, which was the Toml nationalist

00:01:27.860 --> 00:01:34.160
organizing newspaper and website, launched in 1997, the same year

00:01:34.180 --> 00:01:35.610
that the New York Times went online.

00:01:37.660 --> 00:01:42.320
Gapas revolutionaries were using tripod and early hosting service

00:01:42.320 --> 00:01:44.550
in the early '90s to organize, as were Malays

00:01:44.580 --> 00:01:46.100
ian independence activists.

00:01:46.110 --> 00:01:51.660
So, we have a whole alternative history of the use of

00:01:51.660 --> 00:01:57.820
the Internet for political activism and for resistance.

00:01:57.880 --> 00:02:03.220
So, today, something like 25 countries are full democracies

00:02:03.220 --> 00:02:10.300
, out of 184, 85, and only 75 or

00:02:10.300 --> 00:02:12.100
so have democratic forms as a whole.

00:02:12.140 --> 00:02:15.940
So, most people in the world have a very different relationship

00:02:15.940 --> 00:02:21.000
with their governments and their understanding of what regulatory authority can do

00:02:21.180 --> 00:02:28.460
and their understanding of what openness means in the context of societies

00:02:28.460 --> 00:02:28.980
.

00:02:29.020 --> 00:02:34.540
And I want to use that as a basis for trying to

00:02:34.540 --> 00:02:39.530
establish some basic terms about what we mean by authoritarianism.

00:02:39.580 --> 00:02:42.640
So, digital authoritarianism is a term that's been kind

00:02:42.640 --> 00:02:44.840
of in vogue for the past five or six years,

00:02:44.880 --> 00:02:48.850
and it describes very basically the use of technology to advance rep

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:50.480
ressive political interests.

00:02:50.520 --> 00:02:53.320
A slightly older and I think more apt term is networked

00:02:53.320 --> 00:02:56.980
authoritarianism, which emphasizes the idea that people can be co

00:02:56.980 --> 00:03:01.610
-opted into supporting authoritarian power by participating in information systems

00:03:01.640 --> 00:03:01.840
.

00:03:01.880 --> 00:03:04.660
So, apologies if a lot of this is a little bit

00:03:04.670 --> 00:03:07.920
dense, but there's a -- and maybe folks that you

00:03:07.940 --> 00:03:10.850
all know all this already, and apologies if that's true

00:03:10.850 --> 00:03:13.080
, but I feel like it's helpful to establish some kind

00:03:13.080 --> 00:03:15.720
of grounding terminology and definitions.

00:03:15.760 --> 00:03:23.560
In this space, the kind of epistemic challenges,

00:03:23.560 --> 00:03:27.400
the idea that our information spaces are broken and fragmented,

00:03:27.440 --> 00:03:31.060
as we heard so eloquently this morning, the idea that

00:03:31.120 --> 00:03:34.280
that's true is not solely an artifact of our technological afford

00:03:34.440 --> 00:03:37.120
ances and underlying financial incentives.

00:03:37.160 --> 00:03:41.310
In many cases, this is the result of intentional efforts by

00:03:41.310 --> 00:03:45.520
people with power to shape narrative, to persuade and influence,

00:03:45.520 --> 00:03:51.320
to simultaneously narrow spaces for expression and political action, through regulatory

00:03:51.320 --> 00:03:53.700
and through technological approaches.

00:03:53.740 --> 00:03:56.590
So, this isn't happening organically as a result of

00:03:56.600 --> 00:03:57.880
market artifacts.

00:03:57.920 --> 00:04:00.700
That's also important, but it's not only that.

00:04:00.740 --> 00:04:03.610
And in defining the threat, we can also define the fields

00:04:03.640 --> 00:04:04.710
of contestation.

00:04:04.840 --> 00:04:09.540
And I'm not going to read this to you.

00:04:09.600 --> 00:04:10.900
You can read it yourself.

00:04:10.910 --> 00:04:19.670
But in general, authoritarianism has a -- it's useful

00:04:19.670 --> 00:04:23.080
to give it a tight and narrow definition so that we can

00:04:23.080 --> 00:04:23.600
talk about it.

00:04:23.640 --> 00:04:25.920
There are many definitions of authoritarianism.

00:04:25.960 --> 00:04:28.480
This is the one that I'm working with.

00:04:28.520 --> 00:04:32.210
And I find it to be useful because it allows us to

00:04:32.210 --> 00:04:37.980
talk about authoritarian practices and not just authoritarian states.

00:04:38.020 --> 00:04:43.600
So, you can have authoritarianism as a practice that exists

00:04:43.600 --> 00:04:46.870
within a state that is technically categorized by political scientists as

00:04:46.870 --> 00:04:49.460
not authoritarian.

00:04:49.500 --> 00:04:56.340
And things like appropriate citizen oversight or the use of accountability and

00:04:56.530 --> 00:05:01.550
transparency and legitimacy in the application of technology is key to this

00:05:01.550 --> 00:05:02.420
definition.

00:05:02.460 --> 00:05:06.210
So, even in countries that formerly are democratic, you might

00:05:06.210 --> 00:05:14.210
find evidence of authoritarian practices that significantly affect our ability to

00:05:14.330 --> 00:05:17.950
function in terms of our ability to express ourselves or mobilize or

00:05:18.030 --> 00:05:19.740
build movements.

00:05:19.780 --> 00:05:22.850
And many of us in this room, I'm guessing,

00:05:22.850 --> 00:05:28.740
also live in countries where there is the potential or actual presence

00:05:28.750 --> 00:05:31.970
of democratic backsliding.

00:05:32.100 --> 00:05:34.050
That's a term that I hope everybody understands.

00:05:34.070 --> 00:05:39.950
Basically, it means when democratic governments are suddenly no longer democratic

00:05:40.010 --> 00:05:40.210
.

00:05:40.380 --> 00:05:43.690
And what we're seeing in our geopolitical space, which

00:05:43.690 --> 00:05:47.810
is the kind of the end of the post-World War

00:05:47.880 --> 00:05:50.980
II, potentially the end of the post-World War II

00:05:50.980 --> 00:05:51.930
liberal era.

00:05:51.980 --> 00:05:55.830
And the emergence of a transactional geopolitics that kind of

00:05:55.830 --> 00:05:59.650
threatens to undermine a lot of the basic premises for what we

00:05:59.650 --> 00:06:03.740
mean by openness in the international order.

00:06:03.840 --> 00:06:08.280
And that idea of openness in the international order is twinned

00:06:08.280 --> 00:06:11.820
to the idea of openness in information spaces.

00:06:11.860 --> 00:06:19.060
So, when we, building open, decentralized technologies, use

00:06:19.080 --> 00:06:22.520
language to define what we mean by openness, we are also

00:06:22.550 --> 00:06:25.180
inherently talking about this other history.

00:06:25.220 --> 00:06:28.070
And if that history is now being challenged, what does it

00:06:28.080 --> 00:06:29.500
mean for us in this room?

00:06:29.510 --> 00:06:37.410
More specifically, on the left, this is what authoritarianism

00:06:37.580 --> 00:06:38.500
does to us.

00:06:39.620 --> 00:06:44.230
Pluralistic ignorance, which means the fact that you don

00:06:44.230 --> 00:06:46.480
't know, I don't know what you're thinking,

00:06:46.550 --> 00:06:48.950
you don't know what I'm thinking, we have no

00:06:48.950 --> 00:06:52.500
idea that we might have some ideas in common.

00:06:52.540 --> 00:06:56.370
Social isolation and epistemic vertigo, which means that

00:06:56.370 --> 00:06:59.100
we have no basis for common knowledge.

00:06:59.140 --> 00:07:02.840
These are the challenges that our information spaces are creating for us

00:07:02.840 --> 00:07:03.100
.

00:07:03.140 --> 00:07:04.780
And again, we heard a lot about that this morning,

00:07:04.780 --> 00:07:07.100
so I don't necessarily feel a need to repeat myself or

00:07:07.100 --> 00:07:09.540
repeat what was said.

00:07:09.620 --> 00:07:12.620
And then our goals on the right, and this is a

00:07:12.620 --> 00:07:15.420
set of normative claims, like, I'm for these

00:07:15.450 --> 00:07:17.020
things, so I'm not going to pretend that I'm

00:07:17.020 --> 00:07:17.300
not.

00:07:17.340 --> 00:07:22.120
Shared reality, collective action, information integrity, values that

00:07:22.220 --> 00:07:26.300
support more democratic participation, more shared power.

00:07:26.310 --> 00:07:29.710
That's what's at stake.

00:07:36.590 --> 00:07:40.830
Before, so I am the executive chair of the newly formed

00:07:40.830 --> 00:07:44.800
Modal Foundation, which is the entity, the legal entity

00:07:44.800 --> 00:07:46.050
behind Eurosky.

00:07:46.070 --> 00:07:50.260
And I've been in this role and working in this space

00:07:50.270 --> 00:07:51.800
for about eight months.

00:07:51.840 --> 00:07:57.040
Before that, I spent a huge chunk of my life working

00:07:57.110 --> 00:08:01.460
in countries and contexts that were politically contested.

00:08:01.500 --> 00:08:05.470
And I spent the last decade working on research in information ecosystems

00:08:05.620 --> 00:08:05.820
.

00:08:05.860 --> 00:08:08.730
The last big project I did was called the Unfreedom

00:08:08.760 --> 00:08:12.690
Monitor, in which I did a 20-country study of

00:08:12.880 --> 00:08:19.940
the relationship between technology, regulatory structures, and narrative power.

00:08:20.900 --> 00:08:27.360
And the essence of that idea is that regulatory and technical systems

00:08:27.360 --> 00:08:32.450
are being used to narrow the space for expression and political participation

00:08:32.450 --> 00:08:32.610
.

00:08:33.360 --> 00:08:39.430
And the authorities in many countries are using that resultantly narrow

00:08:39.460 --> 00:08:43.580
ed space to amplify a set of narratives to try to convince

00:08:43.660 --> 00:08:47.980
people to give up their rights and freedoms in exchange for their

00:08:47.980 --> 00:08:48.490
safety.

00:08:48.540 --> 00:08:52.480
And I found that to be true in many different political contexts

00:08:52.480 --> 00:08:54.650
in countries around the world.

00:08:54.700 --> 00:08:57.240
And this was a participatory research project.

00:08:57.280 --> 00:08:59.000
About 30 of us worked on it over a two-year

00:08:59.000 --> 00:08:59.500
period.

00:08:59.540 --> 00:09:06.610
Very briefly, looking at this topic, authoritarian strategies involve coerc

00:09:06.690 --> 00:09:10.400
ion, co-optation, and persuasion.

00:09:10.440 --> 00:09:13.220
So I'm not going to define them too carefully.

00:09:13.230 --> 00:09:14.460
I think you understand what they mean.

00:09:14.500 --> 00:09:16.800
Fields of contestation, I already mentioned.

00:09:16.840 --> 00:09:19.800
And then the primary actors, states, cooperations, and

00:09:19.800 --> 00:09:20.420
publics.

00:09:20.460 --> 00:09:27.230
And we found in this research that countries have become very ad

00:09:27.230 --> 00:09:34.160
ept at remixing these different fields in order to create fields

00:09:34.160 --> 00:09:36.260
of repression.

00:09:36.300 --> 00:09:39.170
And it's very hard to contest.

00:09:39.220 --> 00:09:41.910
So I'm going to give one simple example that many of

00:09:41.940 --> 00:09:43.620
you are probably aware of.

00:09:43.660 --> 00:09:45.120
That's the Twitter files.

00:09:45.160 --> 00:09:46.600
Everybody know what the Twitter files was?

00:09:46.640 --> 00:09:47.720
Anybody not know?

00:09:47.750 --> 00:09:51.720
Twitter files was an information operation.

00:09:51.760 --> 00:09:55.320
And it was a group of, I'll call them political

00:09:55.440 --> 00:10:00.340
operatives or information operatives, who claimed that the Biden

00:10:00.350 --> 00:10:06.840
administration in the United States was censoring expression around vaccine,

00:10:06.850 --> 00:10:12.440
around vaccine communications, and trying to force the social media companies

00:10:12.440 --> 00:10:18.150
to remove anti-vax narratives and misinformation and disinformation

00:10:18.150 --> 00:10:18.440
.

00:10:18.480 --> 00:10:23.580
It was untrue, but it crossed all of these fields

00:10:23.580 --> 00:10:25.320
in its architecture.

00:10:25.580 --> 00:10:28.880
And it was very, very successful as an information operation.

00:10:28.920 --> 00:10:34.430
It targeted information integrity researchers, and it destroyed the field of

00:10:34.430 --> 00:10:38.700
information research in the United States as a result.

00:10:39.120 --> 00:10:42.340
These were the people who were exposing truths on the platform,

00:10:42.350 --> 00:10:46.800
studying the platforms, and identifying systemic problems on the platforms.

00:10:46.840 --> 00:10:50.400
They did this by creating a false narrative of state censorship.

00:10:52.820 --> 00:10:56.490
That's the narrative one of having a political ally take over

00:10:56.500 --> 00:11:00.660
Twitter and changing the algorithm to change what we could see.

00:11:00.700 --> 00:11:05.730
Spinning up a false congressional investigation and suing the individual

00:11:05.730 --> 00:11:10.040
researchers who were involved in doing the research in the first place

00:11:10.040 --> 00:11:10.280
.

00:11:10.840 --> 00:11:14.660
And finally, pressuring the institutions and funders of this

00:11:14.660 --> 00:11:18.730
research with the threats of even greater losses in the event that

00:11:18.860 --> 00:11:20.690
they didn't defund this work.

00:11:20.740 --> 00:11:24.900
And that was both state entities and private entities that were funding

00:11:24.900 --> 00:11:26.420
this type of research.

00:11:27.300 --> 00:11:30.990
And the result is decimated field of analysis, less knowledge

00:11:30.990 --> 00:11:38.270
, more social isolation, and more epistemic vertigo

00:11:38.280 --> 00:11:38.890
.

00:11:38.940 --> 00:11:43.120
Very briefly, this is the Information Monitor project.

00:11:43.160 --> 00:11:47.020
I mentioned it already, so I'm just going to very

00:11:47.020 --> 00:11:52.760
briefly talk through some themes in terms of understanding how we think

00:11:52.760 --> 00:11:54.520
about the system.

00:11:55.300 --> 00:11:59.240
Four big categories of information space.

00:11:59.280 --> 00:12:02.260
Access, data governance, information, and speech.

00:12:02.300 --> 00:12:05.900
These are all contested areas where the battle over rights and

00:12:05.980 --> 00:12:08.980
freedoms in information spaces are happening.

00:12:08.990 --> 00:12:17.810
Social controls that governments and states are applying through

00:12:17.810 --> 00:12:20.080
those fields.

00:12:20.120 --> 00:12:24.630
Freedom restrictions, information manipulation, internet control, surveillance, system

00:12:24.680 --> 00:12:25.240
management.

00:12:25.300 --> 00:12:27.440
Freedom attacks, and technology controls.

00:12:27.480 --> 00:12:30.400
I can come back to these later if you want me to

00:12:30.400 --> 00:12:30.700
.

00:12:30.710 --> 00:12:32.810
I'm going to get on to open social protocols fast,

00:12:32.810 --> 00:12:35.130
so I'm just going to zip through these so you have

00:12:35.130 --> 00:12:35.800
a sense.

00:12:35.840 --> 00:12:39.300
This is published documentation, and I can direct you to it

00:12:39.300 --> 00:12:41.040
if you want to read it later.

00:12:42.320 --> 00:12:45.690
And lastly, the types of concrete harms that people experience.

00:12:45.740 --> 00:12:49.500
Intimidation, judicial, physical, and technical are

00:12:49.500 --> 00:12:53.280
broad categories, and these are kind of extensible issues.

00:12:53.320 --> 00:12:56.990
The things that happen to individuals or groups as a result of

00:12:57.000 --> 00:13:01.250
participating in trying to express or participate in civic life.

00:13:06.840 --> 00:13:07.310
Okay.

00:13:07.360 --> 00:13:10.280
Open social as a field of contestation.

00:13:10.320 --> 00:13:15.410
I have two more slides only, and then we'll hopefully

00:13:15.410 --> 00:13:19.020
have about 10 minutes to talk.

00:13:19.060 --> 00:13:25.170
Open social technologies like ATProto and everything that we're

00:13:25.380 --> 00:13:30.410
doing here today have the potential to offer a structural response to

00:13:30.410 --> 00:13:34.120
the primary levers of control that we're experiencing.

00:13:34.160 --> 00:13:37.860
So coercion, resistance, co-option, exit

00:13:37.860 --> 00:13:41.000
, persuasion, algorithmic agency.

00:13:41.260 --> 00:13:45.600
And we have a bunch of potential tools available to us that

00:13:45.600 --> 00:13:50.240
the kinds of technologies that we're building enable us, that

00:13:50.570 --> 00:13:52.520
allow us or help us to act.

00:13:52.660 --> 00:13:59.480
And these are shared truths in public data that's kind of

00:13:59.480 --> 00:14:06.140
a core backbone of what it means to build open public information

00:14:06.140 --> 00:14:09.030
as a ballast or as a counterweight to attempts to

00:14:09.040 --> 00:14:10.060
create isolation.

00:14:10.730 --> 00:14:15.540
Information and identity provenance, data ownership, decentralization,

00:14:15.640 --> 00:14:19.200
and as a mechanism for resilience, as a mechanism for economic

00:14:19.200 --> 00:14:21.780
and technological and informational resilience.

00:14:21.820 --> 00:14:25.790
Cooperative models that allow us to share resources and drive costs

00:14:25.940 --> 00:14:26.460
down.

00:14:26.500 --> 00:14:30.020
And the idea that we can actually use different states and their

00:14:30.180 --> 00:14:33.080
sovereignty, a strategic depth for resistance.

00:14:33.120 --> 00:14:38.320
So we have the option of other jurisdictions to support actions.

00:14:38.420 --> 00:14:41.960
There are others, other affordances and other things that could

00:14:42.100 --> 00:14:42.680
be built.

00:14:42.720 --> 00:14:44.510
And that's kind of going to be the question in the

00:14:44.510 --> 00:14:44.890
room.

00:14:44.940 --> 00:14:51.050
The counterweight is what does this kind of reliance on

00:14:51.260 --> 00:14:54.520
an open system expose us to?

00:14:55.500 --> 00:14:57.410
One is that provenance becomes evidence.

00:14:57.460 --> 00:15:01.390
You know, immutable provenance of information and identity also

00:15:01.390 --> 00:15:02.480
creates risk.

00:15:02.490 --> 00:15:06.400
Public data and context remix.

00:15:06.440 --> 00:15:09.600
So once you put something out into a public network, somebody

00:15:09.600 --> 00:15:12.240
else can take it and put it somewhere else out of your

00:15:12.240 --> 00:15:12.980
control.

00:15:13.700 --> 00:15:18.110
And that is, that's a feature in our system when

00:15:18.110 --> 00:15:23.020
we have a guarantee of a non-authoritarian state that

00:15:23.020 --> 00:15:26.420
is actually available to adjudicate, you know, ad

00:15:26.440 --> 00:15:30.990
judicate your rights in a way that is legitimate and equitable

00:15:30.990 --> 00:15:31.220
.

00:15:31.260 --> 00:15:33.660
And when it's not, when that's not true,

00:15:33.670 --> 00:15:35.440
it becomes a serious risk.

00:15:37.060 --> 00:15:40.220
We've already seen that states are quite adept at identifying

00:15:40.230 --> 00:15:44.410
vulnerable targets within networks of activists, within networks of people who

00:15:44.410 --> 00:15:48.380
express themselves or use open technologies as a way of breaking collective

00:15:48.380 --> 00:15:49.080
action.

00:15:49.120 --> 00:15:53.730
Picking off vulnerable individuals or groups, making examples of them

00:15:53.730 --> 00:15:57.370
in ways that are silencing or suppressing and create fear

00:15:57.370 --> 00:15:59.580
that suffuse civic networks.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:04.290
And resource scarcity because a lot of us are enthusiasts, a

00:16:04.290 --> 00:16:06.680
lot of us are doing this out of a passion.

00:16:06.720 --> 00:16:09.570
And you can do that until you're hit by a slap

00:16:09.570 --> 00:16:12.780
lawsuit or until you're hit by any kind of, like

00:16:12.780 --> 00:16:17.250
, serious legal counterweight that can absorb years of your life

00:16:17.250 --> 00:16:19.160
and all of your savings.

00:16:19.340 --> 00:16:22.900
So lawfare, that's commonly called.

00:16:22.940 --> 00:16:25.250
Narrative power and market pressure.

00:16:25.300 --> 00:16:28.560
Those are the forces that are often arrayed against open networks

00:16:28.560 --> 00:16:28.760
.

00:16:30.600 --> 00:16:32.160
So that's the end of what I have to say.

00:16:32.200 --> 00:16:35.530
I hope that will help us to think about and frame as

00:16:35.550 --> 00:16:39.030
a, think about it and create a frame for this moment

00:16:39.140 --> 00:16:39.460
.

00:16:39.520 --> 00:16:41.760
And I'd be super happy to hear what others have to

00:16:41.760 --> 00:16:42.700
say about this.

00:16:42.740 --> 00:16:44.810
If we have, we have about five minutes.

00:16:44.860 --> 00:16:46.930
